# 45_proj_save_as_smoke — second verb on the proj headless-verb
# singleton (s247 m1). First path-argument verb on the project surface;
# first live exercise of curvz::scripting::path_is_safe under user-
# supplied input.
#
# Tier 4 row remains at 1/~4-5: this smoke does not tick the row
# (per the Tier 4 contract — one tick per shipped singleton, not per
# verb on an already-shipped singleton). The signal here is the
# verb-surface widening, not a scoreboard advance.
#
# ── What this smoke exercises ─────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Scripter context refuses save_as at the dispatcher BEFORE the verb's
# body runs. save_as is declared as ctx::TestRunner only in
# ProjScriptable::context_mask — per CANON's RunContext pseudocode
# line `register_verb("save_as", ctx::TestRunner)` and the Scripter's
# "out of scope" line naming "proj save_as <arbitrary-path>" as
# use-GUI-Save-As territory.
#
# What this smoke CAN observe from Scripter:
#
#   - Every save_as call refuses with the standard RunContext refusal
#     message, regardless of the path argument. The path-safety check
#     wired inside the verb body is structurally unreachable from
#     Scripter (the gate fires first). This is the design — the same
#     pattern smoke 43 confirms via inspector diagnose_test_runner_only.
#
#   - The project's path is unchanged after every refused call. The
#     RunContext gate is a structured early-return; no state mutation
#     happens. The `proj has_path` query before and after each refusal
#     is the assertable observable.
#
# What this smoke CANNOT observe from Scripter:
#
#   - path_is_safe's accept/refuse split as exercised through the
#     save_as verb body. The verb body is wired with the path-safety
#     pre-flight live (any TestRunner caller will exercise it), but
#     from this caller the body never runs. Live path_is_safe coverage
#     for save_as waits for the future CLI test runner.
#
#   - path_is_safe's predicate matrix is exercised separately by
#     smoke 43 via inspector diagnostic queries (home_root_is_safe,
#     tmp_root_is_safe, etc_is_safe, slash_is_safe, empty_is_safe).
#     The predicate IS covered today; only the predicate-as-called-
#     from-save_as-body integration coverage is deferred.
#
# Three refuse cases are exercised below to demonstrate that the gate
# fires regardless of what path was supplied:
#
#   - A safe path under /tmp (the path WOULD be accepted by
#     path_is_safe if the body ran; the gate refuses anyway).
#   - An unsafe path under /etc (the path WOULD be refused by
#     path_is_safe; the gate refuses first).
#   - An empty path (the path WOULD be refused by path_is_safe
#     and also by the arg-validation guard; the gate refuses first).
#
# All three observable outcomes are identical from the dispatcher's
# perspective: same structured refusal line, no project mutation,
# no body execution. That uniformity IS the structural property
# the smoke confirms.
#
# ── Caller context ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# This smoke runs through ScripterWindow's listener, m_context =
# RunContext::Scripter (set in ScripterWindow's ctor, see s244 m2
# wiring). save_as declares its mask as ctx::TestRunner only, so the
# dispatcher's context_allows check returns false on every save_as
# invoke from this caller.
#
# Third consumer of Scriptable::context_mask() in the codebase —
# first was InspectorScriptable's diagnostic surface (s244 m2),
# second was ProjScriptable's `save` mask (s246 m1). The registry-
# promotion clock has reached 3/3 and is HELD by design (s247 m1
# decision — see ProjScriptable.hpp's context_mask block).
#
# ── Test isolation ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# No mutation. Every save_as call refuses at the dispatcher gate
# before any state touches the project. The smoke does NOT write to
# disk — the /tmp/curvz_smoke_45_test.curvz path named below is
# never actually opened for writing because the gate refuses first.
# Repeatable without setup or teardown; safe to run against any
# project state Scott has loaded.
#
# Contrast with smoke 44 (proj save), which DOES write to disk —
# the dispatcher accepts `save` from Scripter (its mask includes
# Scripter), so the verb body runs and the project file's
# last-saved timestamp is refreshed. Smoke 45 does no such write
# because the gate refuses first.

#[sub] === Phase 1: project state precondition ===

#[sub] Get the project's current directory path. Operator-visual:
#[sub] this should be the .curvz directory Scott has open right now.
#[sub] The has_path assertion below confirms the precondition for
#[sub] the post-refusal sanity checks (path unchanged after each
#[sub] refused call) — if has_path is false here, the sanity checks
#[sub] are meaningless because there's no path to be unchanged.

get proj path

assert proj has_path == true

#[sub] === Phase 2: RunContext refusal — safe path ===

#[sub] Call save_as with a path that path_is_safe WOULD accept if
#[sub] the body ran (under /tmp, the canonical safe scratch
#[sub] location). The expected trace line is:
#[sub]
#[sub]   error invoke refused: verb 'save_as' on 'proj' not
#[sub]   permitted in scripter context
#[sub]
#[sub] Operator-visual on the refusal: read the line below this
#[sub] comment in the trace and confirm the structured refusal
#[sub] appears. The DSL's `assert` is equality-only on query
#[sub] results and can't directly compare against the listener's
#[sub] error line; same convention as smoke 43's Phase 5.

proj save_as "/tmp/curvz_smoke_45_test.curvz"

#[sub] === Phase 3: post-refusal sanity (path unchanged) ===

#[sub] After the refused invoke, the project's directory is
#[sub] unchanged. The RunContext gate is a structured early-return
#[sub] (the verb body never ran), so no path assignment happened.
#[sub] This assertion is the structural property that justifies
#[sub] calling save_as a "refused" verb rather than a "partially
#[sub] failed" verb: refusal means zero side effects, full stop.

assert proj has_path == true

#[sub] === Phase 4: RunContext refusal — unsafe path ===

#[sub] Call save_as with a path that path_is_safe WOULD refuse if
#[sub] the body ran (under /etc, outside both $HOME and $TMPDIR).
#[sub] From Scripter context, the dispatcher refuses first — the
#[sub] path_is_safe check inside the verb body is never reached.
#[sub] Same refusal line text as Phase 2; the path argument doesn't
#[sub] affect the gate's decision.
#[sub]
#[sub] This is the structural property the smoke is here to confirm:
#[sub] the RunContext gate fires independent of path safety. A
#[sub] script-supplied unsafe path is refused by the gate just like
#[sub] a script-supplied safe path is — there is no "would have been
#[sub] accepted by path_is_safe so the gate should let it through"
#[sub] backdoor.

proj save_as "/etc/curvz_smoke_45_test.curvz"

#[sub] === Phase 5: RunContext refusal — empty path ===

#[sub] Call save_as with an empty path. Same refusal at the gate;
#[sub] the verb body's argument-validation guard ("path argument is
#[sub] empty or not a string") is also unreached. Three different
#[sub] argument shapes, three identical structured refusals.

proj save_as ""

#[sub] === Phase 6: post-refusal sanity ===

#[sub] Final sanity assertion: the project's path is still unchanged
#[sub] after all three refusals. Confirms the dispatcher's
#[sub] refuse-without-touching-state contract held across multiple
#[sub] gate fires in a row.

assert proj has_path == true

#[sub] s247 m1 smoke complete. Expected summary line:
#[sub]
#[sub]   7 lines, 3 pass, 0 fail, 3 error
#[sub]
#[sub] - 3 PASS  : has_path == true at Phases 1, 3, 6 (path unchanged
#[sub]             across the refusals)
#[sub] - 3 error : the three save_as RunContext refusals at Phases
#[sub]             2, 4, 5 (intentional — the gate working as
#[sub]             designed, one error per refused call per
#[sub]             ScriptListener's ++m_stats.errors at the gating
#[sub]             site)
#[sub] - 1 operator-visual : the `get proj path` echo at Phase 1
#[sub]             (shows which .curvz directory Scott has open)
#[sub] - 3 operator-visual refusals : the structured `error invoke
#[sub]             refused: verb 'save_as' on 'proj' not permitted in
#[sub]             scripter context` line under each refused save_as
#[sub]             call. Read in trace to confirm the refusal text
#[sub]             matches across all three.
#[sub]
#[sub] Tier 4 row stays at 1/~4-5 (no tick — same singleton, second
#[sub] verb). Surface widening: `proj` Scriptable verb count goes
#[sub] 1 → 2; path_is_safe gains its first production call site
#[sub] (live in the verb body even if Scripter context never reaches
#[sub] it); context_mask() consumer count goes 2 → 3 (registry-
#[sub] promotion clock held at 3/3 by design).

#[sub] ── Manual exercise for the verb body ──────────────────────
#[sub]
#[sub] To exercise the save_as verb body's accept and refuse paths
#[sub] (path_is_safe live, do_save_as called), the script needs to
#[sub] run under RunContext::TestRunner. No CLI test runner exists
#[sub] today; this is a backlog item (s244 m2 handoff was explicit).
#[sub] When the test runner lands, an analogue of this smoke will
#[sub] flip Phases 2/4/5 from operator-visual refusal observations
#[sub] to assertable accept/refuse observations on the resulting
#[sub] project path and on-disk file existence.
#[sub]
#[sub] In the meantime, the verb body is wired live and ready —
#[sub] the path_is_safe pre-flight, the argument-validation guards,
#[sub] and the script_save_project_as helper delegation all
#[sub] compile and link, even though today's caller can't reach
#[sub] them through the dispatcher's gating.
